  Anna Skawinska wrote:
  &gt; Hi guys,
  &gt;
  &gt; The reason I started to learn JUnit and Java in general is that I&#39;ve
  &gt; just begun my internship and I&#39;m going to write unit tests for an
  &gt; existing application, developed by &quot;real&quot; programmers :)
  &gt;
  &gt; The application I&#39;m going to work on first is a Java applet, so I&#39;ve
  &gt; focused on finding out how to use JUnit to test them. Having done some
  &gt; experiments, I&#39;ve tried to find some sample projects to show me if I
  &gt; just do it the right way, but unfortunately I haven&#39;t found much.
  &gt;
  &gt; That&#39;s why I&#39;d be extremely grateful if someone will just take a look
  &gt; at what I&#39;ve written and tell me if I have the right idea of using
  &gt; JUnit to test applet-based applications and if I&#39;ll be able to test
  &gt; real, functional applets this way in the future.

  Two of your three test methods don&#39;t test scenarios that would ever
  exist in the real world. You&#39;ll never really put the applet in a JFrame,
  so toss appletNotNull() and frameContentPaneIncludesApplet(). The third
  test method, appletComponentsCountOK(), is reasonable, but
  underspecified, as it doesn&#39;t test whether the applet&#39;s content pane
  contains a JLabel with the name that you gave it.

  For real-world applets, you should consider the following:

  * Refactor the applet so that it&#39;s a thin shell around the content and
  the business logic that acts on the content. In other words, create a
  class that handles all of the layout, then pass an instance of this
  class to the applet&#39;s setContentPane(). This has at least two advantages:
  1) the standalone component can then be tested using one of the Swing
  testing tools, such as JFCUnit, Abbot & Costello, etc.
  2) the standalone component can be dropped into a JFrame to create a
  standalone version of your application. In my experience, it&#39;s much,
  much faster to develop a standalone app than an applet, especially if
  that applet has to be deployed to a Web server (as opposed to the
  appletrunner) in order to confirm your changes. And if deployment of the
  applet is via a .war or .ear, then your time savings are even greater.

  * Applets have several getters for external information, and most
  real-world applets call one or more of these. These would be difficult,
  if not impossible, to test without jumping through several hoops. For
  example, your test&#39;s before() method may have to do something like this:

  Applet app = new AppletClass() {

     public String getAppletInfo() { return &quot;info&quot;; }

     public getAppletContext() { return new CustomAppletContext(); }

     public URL getCodeBase() {
       try {
         return new URL(&quot;file:///my/codebase&quot;);
       } catch (MalformedURLException mux) {
         return null;
     }

     // etc.
  }

  Some of these, like the ApplicationContext, are rather rich interfaces
  that would be a pain in the a$$ to mock out if they have to do anything
  meaningful.

  It would be much, much easier to factor out the applet logic, per the
  first bullet-point above, into standalone components that can take some
  of this information in the form of something like properties. For
  example, say your (signed) applet needs a URL for connecting to a remote
  database, and this URL is specified in a &lt;param&gt; tag inside the &lt;applet&gt;
  tag on the HTML page. The applet&#39;s init() will read the URL from the
  applet context and pass it to the factored-out code, like so:

  public class AppletClass extends JApplet {
     public void init() {
       String dbUrlStr = getParameter(&quot;db.url&quot;);
       JPanel content = new ApplicationPanel(dbUrlStr);
       setContentPane(content);
     }
  }

  A standalone app or a test would get the URL in a different way:

  @test public void constructAppPanelWithValidUrl() {
     String urlStr = &quot;http://my.db.url&quot;;
     JPanel content = new ApplicationPanel(dbUrlStr);
     // assert that the connection is valid, etc.
  }

